<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-06-24T09:50:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-06-24T09:50:00-05:00" n="569" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d569">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">724.3415/1232: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Paraguay</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Horn</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Asunción</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-06-24T11:00:00-03:50">June 24, 1931—11
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received 3:25 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>61. My 60, June 23, 11 a.m.<note n="67" xml:id="d569fn67">See footnote
                                65, <hi rend="italic">supra.</hi></note> Reply of Paraguayan
                            Government dated yesterday and delivered to Bolivian Minister this
                            morning expresses regret that Bolivia’s request for discrediting Ynsfran
                            should have been coupled by threat to suspend diplomatic relations.
                            Paraguayan note considers incident complained of as of slight
                            consequence and refuses to comply with Bolivia’s request. I am told text
                            of both Bolivian and Paraguayan notes will be published in today’s
                            papers.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Horn</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>